"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s7",
"title":{
"__html":"Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"59df17",
"children":[
"Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s7_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"399700",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"hypertrophic cardiomyopathy",
"children":[
"HCM"
]
},
" is an uncommon primary cardiac disease characterized by diffuse or focal myocardial hypertrophy. The disease is genetically inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern. Most patients are asymptomatic but may present with ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"heart failure",
"children":[
"HF"
]
},
","
]
},
" palpitations, syncope, or sudden cardiac death (",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"sudden cardiac death",
"children":[
"SCD"
]
},
"). HF symptoms are attributable to abnormal diastolic dysfunction and dynamic left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) obstruction."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_cv_s7_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s7_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d02eaf",
"children":[
"The ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"electrocardiogram",
"children":[
"ECG"
]
},
" shows ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"left ventricular",
"children":[
"LV"
]
},
" hypertrophy and left atrial enlargement. Deeply inverted, symmetric T waves in leads V",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"3"
]
},
" to V",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"6"
]
},
" are present in the apical hypertrophic form of the disease (mimics ischemia). Echocardiography demonstrates the degree and distribution of hypertrophy and the degree of ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"left ventricular outflow tract",
"children":[
"LVOT"
]
},
" obstruction and mitral regurgitation. 48-Hour ambulatory ECG monitoring is performed to evaluate for arrhythmias."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s7_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"74f2b2",
"children":[
"Patients with HCM should avoid competitive sports and intense isometric exercise. β-Blockers are first-line agents for patients with an ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"ejection fraction",
"children":[
"EF"
]
},
" ≥50%, dyspnea, and/or chest pain. Calcium channel blockers (verapamil or diltiazem) may be substituted for β-blockers. Disopyramide may be added if significant symptoms related to LVOT obstruction remain. ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"angiotensin-converting enzyme",
"children":[
"ACE"
]
},
" inhibitors are used only if systolic dysfunction is present."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"59cbf1",
"children":[
"Anticoagulate all patients with ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"atrial fibrillation",
"children":[
"AF"
]
},
" regardless of CHA",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
"DS",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
"-VASc score. Surgery or septal ablation is indicated for patients with an outflow tract gradient of >50 mm Hg and continuing symptoms despite maximal drug therapy. Patients with previous sudden cardiac death or sustained ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"ventricular tachycardia",
"children":[
"VT"
]
},
" should receive an ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"implantable cardioverter defibrillator",
"children":[
"ICD"
]
},
" for secondary prevention."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"df1024",
"children":[
"Avoid vasodilating β-blockers (carvedilol, labetalol, and nebivolol)."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"08e97d",
"children":[
"Electrophysiologic studies are not useful in predicting sudden cardiac death."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"9ba504",
"children":[
"Do not prescribe digoxin, vasodilators, or diuretics, which increase LV outflow obstruction, for patients with HCM."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s7_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Screening"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"db7551",
"children":[
"Screening"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"64678e",
"children":[
"All first-degree relatives of patients with HCM should undergo ECG and echocardiography plus genetic counseling (if sarcomeric mutation is identified in index case). Genetic testing may disclose genotype-positive persons who do not express clinical features of HCM, and ongoing screening is recommended because of the possibility of disease expression at any age. In the absence of a documented genetic mutation in the proband, ongoing screening of first-degree relatives is not indicated."
]
},
